Stochastic Report - September 2024

STOCHASTIC SCENARIO REAL-WORLD TESTS¶

This script checks the consistency of a real-world stochastic scenarios, provided by an outside vendor to the bank. The Economic Scenario Generator (ESG) output consists of 10,000 instances (scenarios) of various financial curves. The goal of this test is to:

  • Verify if the ESG output fulfils the properties that a real-world ESG should have
  • Preform a series of tests that verify if the model behaves as described
  • Verifies if the inputs used to run the model are the same as the ones provided by the bank

Description of the models¶

The models tested in this workbook are two:

  • The Displaced diffusion Libor market model (DDLMM). DDLMM is a stochastic model of forward rates that can be used by the business to generate a yield curve.
  • The Geometric Brownian Motion model (GBM). GBM is a popular model for modelling of total-return indices.

Displaced diffusion LIBOR market model¶

The stochastic differential equation governing the process is given by: $$ dF_i(t) = \mu_i(F(t), t) (F_i(t) + \alpha_i) dt + \sigma_i(t) (F_i(t) + \alpha_i) dW_i(t) $$

Where: $F_k(t) = F(t; T_{k-1}, T_k)$

The forward measure dynamic is:

if $i<k, t\leq T$:

$$ dF_k(t) = \sigma_k(t) (F_k(t) + \alpha) + \sum_{j = i+1}^{k} \frac{\rho_{k,j} \tau_j \sigma_j(t) (F_j(t) + \alpha)}{1 + \tau_j (F_j(t) + \alpha)}dt + \sigma_k(t) (F_k(t) + \alpha) dW_k(t) $$

Geometric Brownian motion model¶

A Geometric Brownian Motion (GBM) model is a stochastic process commonly used in financial modelling to simulate the evolution of asset prices or total-return indices over time. It assumes that the logarithmic returns of the index are normally distributed and incorporates both a deterministic trend (drift) and random shocks (volatility). The model is defined by the stochastic differential equation $$ 𝑑I_k(𝑡) = \mu I_k(𝑡) 𝑑𝑡 + \sigma I_k(𝑡) 𝑑𝑊_𝑡 $$ where $I_t$ represents the index value at time 𝑡, $\mu$ is the drift rate, $\sigma$ is the volatility, and $𝑑𝑊_𝑡$ is a Wiener process. This allows the GBM model to capture the compound growth and the randomness inherent in financial markets, making it suitable for simulating total-return indices.

Description of the stochastic scenario tests¶

The script performs a series of tests, designed to verify if the curves are generated using the correct implementation and correct parameters. The following tests are implemented in this run:

  1. Test 0: Deterministic deflator is equal to the SWAP curve provided by the company
  2. Test 1: Average of the stochastic deflator is equal to the deterministic deflator
  3. Test 2: Martingale test of various trading strategies using spot rates
  4. Test 3: Martingale test of various trading strategies using forward rates
  5. Test 4: Manual calculation of implied swaption value is equal to market swaption value
  6. Test 5: Maximum likelihood estimation for GBM indices is equal to the drifts provided by the company
  7. Test 6: Correlation of all GBM indices is equal to the correlation provided by the company

Limitations of the implementation¶

This implementation only looks at a subset of all scenarios. In particular:

  • Only spot rates with term 1, 2, 3 and 5 years are considered
  • Only a single currency for spot rates and deflators in a single run
  • The exact methodology for calculating implied volatilities was not shared
  • This script assumes that the displacement paramter $\alpha$ is equal to 0

The accounting convention used is that all months are assumed to be of equal length and represent exactly 1/12 of a year.

Success criteria definition¶

The automated tests will compare the mean and the maximum allowed difference between the observed statistics and its theoretical/input value.

The following success thresholds are proposed:

  • Maximum difference between the stochastic curve and the deterministic curve is never larger than 300 bps
  • Average difference between the average of stochastic curve and the deterministic curve is never larger than 500 bps
  • Maximum difference between the observed implied volatility and the modelled one is not larger than 100bps
  • Average difference between the observed implied volatility and the modelled one is not larger than 50bps
  • Maximum difference between the input correlation and the observed correlation of GBM indices is not larger than 10%
  • Average difference between the input correlation and the observed correlation of GBM indices is not larger than 2%
  • Maximum difference between the ML estimated parameters and reported ones is no larger than 10 bps
  • Average difference between the ML estimated parameters and reported ones is no larger than 5 bps

Data requirements¶

To perform this test, the following data is required:

  • Deterministic scenario curves
  • Stochastic scenario curves
  • Real-world spread table
  • Swaption implied volatilities
  • Index correlation matrix
  • Total-return index volatility

External dependencies¶

This implementation uses Python as the underlying programming language. In addition to the basic Python instalation, it uses four Python packages widely used in the financial industry:

  • Pandas (https://pandas.pydata.org/docs/)
  • Numpy (https://numpy.org/doc/)
  • Scipy (https://scipy.org/)
  • Matplotlib (https://matplotlib.org/stable/index.html).

Importing data¶

All seven required input csv files need to be shared in tandom and are imported into the script at once. These files will be used by the script to perform the required tests.

Data manipulation¶

This step converts the raw data from the input file into a format that can be digested by the testing framework. To uniquely identify the correct scenarios, 4 header types are used:

  1. Term ex. 0, 1, 2, 3, ...
  2. Economy ex. EUR, USD, ...
  3. Class ex. GOVT, ZCB, ...
  4. Variable name ex. DEF, SPOT_RATE_PC, ...

Parameter selection¶

  • Currency selected is: "EUR"
  • Country selected is: "SPA"
  • Time fraction set at: 1/12
  • List of swaption tenors: [1, 2, 5, 10, 15]
  • List of swaption maturities: [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 7, 10, 15]
  • Maximum allowed iterations of Newton-Raphson: 10000
  • Accepted tolerance of Newton-Raphson= 0.00001

Real-world to risk-neutral transformation¶

The difference between the risk-neutral and real-world scenarios is a constant spread, applied to the spot curves, defined by the company. To simplify and synchronize the checks, this extra spread is deducted. This, transformed output, is expected to behave similarly to the "risk-neutral" output. Therefore some the risk-neutral tests such as the martingale test can be used. The real-world spread $ s^{RW}_{KT} $ is removed from the annualized spot rate. The example for the spot rate with term of 1 year would be:

$$ r^A_{i, KT}(t, t+12) = r^{A,RW}_{i, KT}(t, t+12) - s^{RW}_{KT} $$

Where:

  • $A$ means that the number is annualized
  • $KT$ means that the spot rate has the term of $K$ years
  • $s^{RW}_{KT}$ is the real-world spread for the spot rate with term of $K$ years
  • $r^{A,RW}_{i, KT}(t, t+12)$ is the real-world spot rate with a term of $K$ years between times $t$ and $t+12$ in the scenario $i$
  • $r^A_{i, KT}(t, t+12) $ is the risk-neutral spot rate with a term of $K$ years between times $t$ and $t+12$ in the scenario $i$

Note that the superscript "RN" is ommited to simplify the notation. Where "RW" is not used, the outout is at the same format as a "RN" output.

Currency and indices selection¶

Each data file contains multiple currencies and curves. In this section, the required curves are extracted. The scope is described in the Limitation section. For each run, only a single currency and a single country is chosen.

Deflator asset; deterministic scenario¶

The deflator asset is represented as a price curve of a risk-free bond with a notional value of 1, issued at time 0 and maturing at time t:

$$ D_{DET, DEF}\big(0, t\big) $$

Where:

  • DET denotes that this zero coupon bond (ZCB) was priced using the deterministic curve
  • DEF denotes that this zero coupon bond represents the deflator
  • 0 is the Issue time
  • t is the Maturity time

Spot rate with a 1-year term; deterministic scenario¶

The spot rate with term of 1-year is one of the simulated financial curves. It is represented as a series of annualized returns. The value at time t represents the return of investing 1 unit of currency at time t until time t+12 (months):

$$ r^A_{DET, 1T}(t, t+12) $$

Where:

  • A denotes that the rate is annualized
  • DET denotes that this is a return calculated using the deterministic scenario curve
  • 1T denotes that this return is calculated using the spot curve with a 1-year term
  • t is the time of investment

Note that the curve is reported in percentages and is normalized by dividing it by 100.

Stochastic scenarios filter¶

Deflator asset; stochastic scenarios¶

The deflator asset is represented as the price curve of a risk-free bond with a notional value of 1, issued at time 0 and maturing at time t. The curves from the stochastic scenarios file do not have the subscript DET, but instead the stochastic scenario number i. This is represented as:

$$ D_{i, DEF}\big(0, t\big) $$

Where:

  • i denotes that this is a stochastic deflator asset from the i-th stochastic scenario
  • DEF denotes that this represents the deflator asset
  • 0 is the Issue time
  • t is the Maturity time

Spot rate with a 1-year term; stochastic scenarios¶

The spot rate with term of 1-year is represented as a series of annualized returns. The value at time t represents the return of investing 1 at time t until time t+12 (months) in scenario i.

$$ r^A_{i, 1T}(t, t+12) $$

Where:

  • i denotes that this is the return calculated using the i-th stochastic scenario
  • 1T denotes that this return is calculated using the spot curve with a 1-year term
  • t is the time of investment
  • A denotes that the curve is annualized (Represents the 1-year return)

Note that the curve is reported in percentages and is normalized by dividing it by 100.

Stochastic deflator performance calculation¶

To calculate the performance of the deflator asset in different time increments, first the monthly return at each time increment t in each scenario i is calculated:

$$ r^{1M}_{i,DEF}(t, t+1) = \frac{ D_{i, DEF} (0, t)}{ D_{i, DEF}(0, t+1)} - 1$$

Annualized (12 months) performance can be calculated as the 12-month rolling product of the monthly capitalisation factor:

$$ r^A_{i,DEF}(t, t+12) = \prod_{j = t}^{t+12}{\big(1+r^{1M}_{i,DEF}(j, j+1)\big)} - 1$$

Where:

  • $D_{i,DEF}\big(0, t\big)$ is the value of the deflator issued at time 0 with a Maturity at time t priced using the i-th scenario
  • $r_{i,DEF}^{1M}(t, t+1)$ is the 1-month return of the deflator asset at time t under the i-th scenario
  • $r^A_{i,DEF}(t, t+12)$ is the yearly (12-month) return of the deflator asset between times t and t+12 under the i-th scenario

Test 0; Input curve is equal to the deterministic¶

This test verifies if the deterministic deflator equals to the input curve, provided by the company.

The test compares the input curve provided by the company with the equivalent curve calculated from the deterministic deflator.

The original curve provided by the business is an annual yield curve. Therefore, the deterministic deflator is transformed into a corresponding yield curve and compared.

$$ y^A_{DET, DEF} (0, t) = \big[D_{DET, DEF}(0, t)\big]^{-\frac{t}{12}}-1 $$

The test verifies the following relation: $$ y_{INPUT} (0,t) =^? y^A_{DET, DEF} (0, t) $$

Where:

  • $t$ is the time of maturity
  • $D_{DET, DEF}(0, t)$ is the deterministic deflator at time $t$
  • $ y^A_{DET, DEF} (0, t) $ is the yield between time $0$ and $t$ calculated from the deterministic deflator curve
  • $y_{INPUT} (0,t)$ is the input yield curve provided by the company to the model provider

Note that the input yield curve is provided on an annual basis while the deflator is a monthly curve. Therefore only every 12-th value of the deflator is compared to the input curve.

The two test statistics used are:

$$ S^0_{AVERAGE} = \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t = 0}^{T} \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N \bigg| y^A_{DET, DEF} (0, t) - y_{INPUT} (0,t) \bigg| $$


$$ S^0_{MAX} = \max_t \bigg|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N y^A_{DET, DEF} (0, t) - y_{INPUT} (0,t) \bigg| $$

Test 1; Mean of stochastic deflator is equal to the deterministic¶

The objective of this test is to compare the average performance of the stochastic deflation asset and the deterministic deflator.

The relationship tested for the spot curves is:

$$ E\bigg[ D_{i, DEF}(0,t) \bigg] =^? D_{DET, DEF} (0,t) $$

The two test statistics used are:

$$ S^1_{AVERAGE} = \frac{1}{T-12} \sum_{t = 0}^{T-12} \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N \bigg| D_{i, DEF}(0,t) - D_{DET, DEF}(0,t) \bigg| $$


$$ S^1_{MAX} = \max_t \bigg|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N D_{i, DEF}(0,t) - D_{DET, DEF}(0,t) \bigg| $$

Where:

  • $N\dots$ is the number scenarios
  • $T\dots$ is the number of time increments
  • $D_{i, DEF}(0,t) \dots$ is the deflator asset between time 0 and t, priced using the stochastic scenario i
  • $D_{DET, DEF}(0,t)\dots$ is the deflator asset between time 0 and t priced using the deterministic scenario
  • $S^1_{AVERAGE}\dots$ is the average test statistics for the first test
  • $S^1_{MAX}\dots$ is the maximum deviation test statistics for the first test

Test 2: Discounted stochastic performance of spot rate with term of K years¶

The purpose of this test is to verify if a simple trading strategy using the spot rates of varying terms are arbitrage free excluding the real-world spread.

The test is performed by simulating a buy-and-hold strategy and calculating the return of such a strategy. If the return of such a strategy is equal to the return of the deflator asset, the discounted process is a Martingale.

The Buy-and-hold strategy consists of investing all funds into ZCBs of a selected maturity, holding them until maturity and rolling all proceeds to buy another round of ZCB with the same selected maturity.

The strategy consists of investing for ex. 1 unit of currency in month k and withdrawing the accrued payoff at time T.

k is one of the first $K*12$ months where $K$ is the term of the spot rate curve used.

This payoff can be replicated by investing the initial amount into the deflator asset at time k and withdrawing everything at the end time T.

If the strategy has a term of K-years, $K*12$ separate starting points need to be tested (to cover the entire curve). For each starting point, the performance can be calculated as:

$$ Perf^{BH}_{i,KT,k} (t`)= \prod_{j = 0}^{t`} \left( (1+r_{i,KT}(k+12 K j) \right)^K $$

Where $t` = 1,2,3,...$. Note that $t`$ represents year multiples of the selected term $K$.

Therefore:

$$ DPerf^{BH}_{i,KT,k} (t`)= E^{Q_k}\big[Perf^{BH}_{i,KT,k} (t`)\big] = Perf^{BH}_{i,KT,k} (t`) * D_{i, RF}(0,k+12 K t`) $$

is a Martingale. The test verifies the following asymptotic identity:

$$ DPerf^{BH}_{i,KT,k} (t`) =^? 1 $$

Where:

  • $Q$ is the numeraire used in this test which is the terminal value of the deflator asset starting at time k

For the second test, the two test statistics used are:

$$ S_{AVERAGE} = \frac{1}{T`} \sum_{t` = 0}^{T`} \frac{1}{N} \big| \sum_{i = 0}^N (DPerf^{BH}_{i,1T,k} (t`) - 1) \big| $$


$$ S_{MAX} = \max_{t`} \bigg| \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N (DPerf^{BH}_{i,1T,k} (t`) - 1) \bigg| $$

Note that the selected spot curve maturities are 1,2,3 and 5.

Test 3; Forward return with a spread of 1-year investment strategy¶

The purpose of this test is to verify if a simple trading strategy using the forward rates satisfies the no-arbitrage property implied by the model.

The test calculates the return of a forward for each period. If the return of this strategy is equal to the deflator's return, then the discounted process would be a Martingale.

Forward return with a spread of 1-year strategy consists of buying and selling fixed income assets in a way that the return is equal to a forward rate with constant maturity. In this example, a constant maturity of 1-year is implemented by buying (long position) a ZCB with a maturity of K+1-years and selling (short position) a ZCB with a maturity of K-years.

$$ D_{i,KT}(t, t+12K) = \frac{1}{\big(1 + r^A_{i, KT}(t, t+12K) \big)^K} $$$$ Perf^{FR}_{i,KT,(K+1)T}(t, t+12K) =\frac{ D_{i,KT}(t, t+12K)}{ D_{i, (K+1)T}(t, t+12K)} = $$$$ = \frac{\frac{1}{\big(1 + r^A_{i, KT}(t, t+12K) \big)^{K}}}{\frac{1}{\big(1 + r^A_{i, (K+1)T}(t, t+12K) \big)^{K+1}}} = \frac{\left( 1 + r^A_{i, (K+1)T}(t, t+12)\right)^{K+1}}{\left( 1 + r^A_{i, KT}(t, t+12) \right)^{K}} $$

Therefore:

$$ DPerf^{FR}_{i,KT,(K+1)T}(t, t+12K) = \frac{Perf^{FR}_{i,KT,(K+1)T}(t, t+12K)}{\big(1+ r^A_{i,DEF}(t+12K)\big)} $$

is a Martingale.

The test verifies the following asymptotic identity:

$$ E^Q\big[Perf^{FR}_{i,KT,(K+1)T}(t, t+12K)\big] =^? 1 $$

In the third test, the two test statistics used are:

$$ S_{AVERAGE} = \frac{1}{T-12} \sum_{t = 0}^{T-12}\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N \big| DPerf^{FR}_{i,KT,(K+1)T}(t, t+12K) - 1 \big| $$
$$ S_{MAX} = \max_t \bigg|\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i = 0}^N (DPerf^{FR}_{i,KT,(K+1)T}(t, t+12K) - 1) \bigg| $$

Where:

  • $Q$ is the numeraire used in this test which is the 1-year forward rate of the deflator
  • $ Perf^{FR}_{i,TK,TK+1}(t) $ Annual return of a forward return strategy, issued at time 0, maturing at time t and priced using the spot curves with term TK and TK+1 in scenario i
  • $ DPerf^{FR}_{i,TK,TK+1}(t) $ Discounted annual return of a forward return strategy, issued at time 0, maturing at time t and priced using the spot curves with term TK and TK+1 in scenario i

Test 4: Manual calculation of swaptions is equal to market swaptions¶

Many classes of models can be calibrated using the swaption volatilities. The purpose of this test is to verify if the empirically calculated swaption implied volatilities are similar to the implied volatilities used in the calibration of the model.

This check calculates the swaption value from the output of the scenario generator. The value of the calculated swaptions should be close to the ones obtained in the market and used in the calibration routine.

The test is performed by calculating the swap rate of the deterministic and stochastic scenarios. This information is then used to calculate the swaption prices using the deterministic swap rate as the strike price. Then a root finding algorithm is used to calculate the implied volatilities assuming a Bachelier model.

To calculate the swaption implied volatilities at each tenor and maturity, the following steps are preformed:

  1. Calculate the swap rate at-the-money of the input risk-free curve
  2. Calculate the annual factors of the at-the-money swap curve
  3. Calculate the relevant swap rate of each scenario
  4. Calculate the swaption value using the risk-free at-the-money swap rate as the strike price
  5. Calculate the average swaption price across scenarios
  6. Calculate the implied volatility of the swaption using the Bachelier model
  7. Use Newton-Rapson to find the implied Volatility
  8. Compare the calculated implied volatilities with the input

The discount factor given a spot curve can be calculated as:

$$ D_{i,jT}(t) = \frac{1}{\big(1 + r^A_{i,jT}(t)\big)^{j}} $$

Step 1: Calculate the swap rate at-the-money of the input risk-free curve¶

$$ SWATM_{DET, RF, M T}(0,t) = \frac{D_{DET, DEF}(0,t) - D_{DET, DEF}(0,t+M))}{\sum_{j = t}^{t+M} D_{DET, DEF}(0,j)} $$

or in Brigo&Mercurio p.18

$$ K_{ATM} = S_{\alpha,\beta}(0) = \frac{P(0,T_{\alpha}) - P(0,T_{\beta})}{\sum_{i =\alpha+1}^{\beta}\tau_i P(0, T_i)} $$

Step 2: Calculate the annual factors of the at-the-money swap curve¶

$$ SWANF_{DET, DEF, M T}(0, t) = \sum_{j = t}^{t+M} D_{DET, DEF, jT}(0,t) $$

or Brigo&Mercurio p.240

$$ C_{\alpha, \beta}(t) = \sum_{i = \alpha+1}^{\beta} \tau_i P(t, T_i) $$

Step 3: Calculate the relevant swap rate of each scenario¶

$$ SWAP_{i, M T}(0, t ) = \frac{1 - D_{i, M T}(0,t)}{\sum_{j = 1}^{M} D_{i, j T}(0, t)} $$

or Brigo&Mercurio p.239 eq(6.33) $$ S_{\alpha, \beta}(t) = \frac{1-\prod_{j =\alpha+1}^{\beta}\frac{1}{1+\tau_j f_j(t)}}{\sum_{i =\alpha+1}^{\beta}\tau_i \prod_{j=\alpha+1}^{i}\frac{1}{1+\tau_jF_j(t)}} $$

Step 4: Calculate the swaption value using the risk-free at-the-money swap rate as the strike price¶

$$ SWAPTION_{i, M T}(0, t) = D_i(0, t) \max{\big[0, SWAP_{i, M T} (0,t) - SWATM_{DET, RF, M T}(0,t)\big]} \sum_{j = 1}^{M} D_{DET, DEF, j T}(0, t) $$

or Brigo&Mercurio p.240 eq(6.36)

$$ D(0, T_{\alpha}) (S_{\alpha, \beta}(T_{\alpha})-K)^{+} \sum_{i=\alpha+1}^{\beta} \tau_i P(T_{\alpha}, T_i) $$

Step 5: Calculate the average swaption price across scenarios¶

$$ SWAPTION_{M T}(0,t) = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{j = 1}^{N} SWAPTION_{j, M T}(0, t) $$

Step 6: Calculate the implied volatility of the payer swaption using the Bachelier model¶

The Bachelier model is used to calculate price of a receiver swaption. The Bachelier model is used with the swap price equal to the strike price. In the next step, the empirical volatility is calibrated so that the price of this swaption is equal to the price calculated using the stochastic scenarios.

$$ d = \frac{Sw-K}{v * \sqrt{T}} $$$$ nd1 = N(d) $$

Payer: $$ price = A \frac{\big( (Sw-K) * nd1 + v*\sqrt{T} e^{-\frac{d^2}{2}} \big)}{\sqrt{2\pi}} $$

Where:

  • $Sw\dots$ forward swap rate
  • $K\dots$ Strike rate of the swaption
  • $v\dots$ Volatility
  • $T\dots$ Maturity
  • $A\dots$ Annuity factor

Step 7: Use Newton-Rapson to find the implied Volatility¶

To calculate the implied volatility of a swaption, we use the fact that the volatility will result in the swaption being in-the-money. A search algorithm is used to find this volatility.

In each step,

  1. Calculate the value of swaption using the current implied volatility guess
  2. Calculate the derivative of the payer swaption w.r.t. the volatility
  3. Use the derivative in the Newton method to adjust implied volatility
  4. If the derivative is flat or algorithm has reached maximum number of iterations, exit

From an initial guess, the algorithm used is:

$$ d = \frac{Sw- K}{v \sqrt{T}} $$$$ dv = \frac{\partial d}{\partial vol}= A \frac{e^{-\frac{d^2}{2}}}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\bigg[ \frac{-(Sw-K) d}{v}+\sqrt{T} + \sqrt{T} d^2\bigg] $$$$ vol = vol-\frac{Func}{dv} $$

Until:

  • $|\frac{Func}{dx}| < \epsilon$
  • $i=MaxIter$

Where:

Func = bachelier_swap(Payer, Sw, K, v T, A, Option Value, Initial Guess)

Where:

  • $Sw\dots$ forward swap rate
  • $K\dots$ Strike
  • $v\dots$ Volatility
  • $T\dots$ Maturity
  • $A\dots$ Annuity factor
  • $OptionValue\dots$ value of the option
  • $guess\dots$ initial guess of the implied volatility

Test 5: Correlation of GBM indices¶

The real-world output contains indices generates from a GBM model. This test verifies that the correlation between the total-return indices is the same as the one provided as input.

This test verifies that the empirical correlation is similar to the correlation stated in the report. The test verifies the following indices:

  • SX5T (EUR)
  • SX5TS (S_EUR)
  • LP01TREU (HY)
  • LUTLTREH (GOVT)
  • SX5T (Infra)
  • SX5T (Propt)
  • LP01TREU (Loans)
  • NDDUUS (USD)
  • LUTLTRUU (GOVT USD)

The test is performed by calculating the Pearson correlation for all selected indices at each individual time-point. This gives a number of correlation matrices equal to the number of time-points in the model. The final empirical correlation is calculated as the mean of these matrices element-wise.

Test 6: Maximum likelihood estimation for GBM¶

The purpose of this test is to verify if the parameters used in the generation of the GBM indices are the same as the ones provided as input.

For each total-return index, a maximum likelihood (ML) parameter estimation is performed. The estimated parameters are then compared to the ones provided as input.

The ML test performs a ML estimation on each scenario. The final estimated parameter is the mean of the estimations. The same procedure is performed for both the mean and the variance parameter.

For an iid sequence of Geometric Brownian motion increments,

$$ f(x_i │ \mu, \sigma^2) = \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{- \frac{(x_i - \mu)^2}{2 \sigma^2}} $$$$ L(\mu, \sigma) = \prod_{i=1}^N f(x_i │ \mu, \sigma^2) =\prod_{i=1}^N \frac{1}{\sigma \sqrt{2 \pi}} e^{- \frac{(x_i - \mu)^2}{2 \sigma^2}} = $$$$ = (\sigma^2)^{-\frac{N}{2}} (2\pi)^{- \frac{N}{2}} e^{-\sum_{i=1}^N \frac{(x_i - \mu)^2}{2 \sigma^2}} = (\sigma^2)^{-\frac{N}{2}} (2\pi)^{- \frac{N}{2}} e^{-\frac{1}{2 \sigma^2}\sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2} $$

The log-likelihood is:

$$ l(\mu, \sigma) = ln(L(\mu, \sigma)) = - \frac{N}{2} ln(\sigma^2) -\frac{N}{2} ln(2 \pi) - \frac{1}{2 \sigma^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2 = $$$$ = - \frac{N}{2} ln(\sigma^2) - \frac{N}{2} ln(2 \pi) - \frac{1}{2 \sigma^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2 $$

The derivation for $\mu$:

$$ \frac{\partial l(\mu, \sigma)}{\partial \mu} = \frac{1}{\sigma^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu) = \frac{1}{\sigma^2}\big[\sum_{i=1}^N x_i - N \mu \big] $$

Second derivative for $\mu$: $$ \frac{\partial^2 l(\mu, \sigma)}{\partial^2 \mu} = -\frac{N}{\sigma^2} $$

The peak is where the derivative is equal to 0 $$ \frac{\partial l(\mu, \sigma)}{\partial \mu} │_{(\mu, \sigma) = (\hat{\mu}, \hat{\sigma})} = 0 $$

$$ \frac{1}{\sigma^2}\bigg[ \sum_{i=1}^N x_i - N \hat{\mu} \bigg] = 0 $$$$ \hat{\mu} = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N x_i $$

The derivation for $\sigma$:

$$ \frac{\partial l(\mu, \sigma)}{\partial \sigma^2} = - \frac{N}{2}\frac{1}{\sigma^2} + \frac{1}{2 (\sigma^2)^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2 $$

The second derivative for $\sigma$ $$ \frac{\partial^2 l(\mu, \sigma)}{\partial^2 \sigma^2} = \frac{N}{2} \frac{1}{(\sigma^2)^2} - \frac{1}{(\sigma^2)^3}\sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \mu)^2 $$

The peak is where the derivative is equal to 0: $$ \frac{\partial l(\mu, \sigma)}{\partial \sigma} │_{(\mu, \sigma) = (\hat{\mu}, \hat{\sigma})} = 0 $$

$$ 0 = - \frac{N}{2} \frac{1}{\hat{\sigma}^2} + \frac{1}{(\hat{\sigma}^2)^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \hat{\mu})^2 $$$$ \frac{N}{2} \frac{1}{\hat{\sigma}^2} = \frac{1}{(\hat{\sigma}^2)^2} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \hat{\mu})^2 $$$$ \hat{\sigma}^2 = \frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N (x_i - \hat{\mu})^2 $$
